    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="167"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1690</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vologda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 18, 1918</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 30, 8.58
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>109. Continuing my 107, 17th. Following just received from
                        <persName>Webster</persName>, Omsk, through <persName corresp="#p_RLCR1"
                        >Robins</persName>: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Leaving 18th for Moscow. Investigations, Krasnoyarsk, Omsk, give entirely
                            satisfactory results confirming impressions communicated previous
                            telegrams. No armed prisoners Krasnoyarsk, discipline strict. Omsk chief
                            center arming prisoners, total, including those sent against <persName
                                corresp="#p_SGG1">Semenov</persName>, 1, 100. Omsk provincial arming
                            prisoners confirmed. Guarantees obtained from All-Siberian Soviet. All
                            armed prisoners violently socialistic. Present conditions without menace
                            except against Central Empires or Japanese invasion.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Mail just received from Consul General enclosing telegrams from <persName
                        corresp="#p_MDB1">Macgowan</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JD1"
                        >Jenkins</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TAR1">Thomson</persName>,
                        <persName>Nielsen</persName>. Do not accord with
                        <persName>Webster</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_MDB1"
                        >Macgowan</persName> reported, 12th, had urged <persName>Webster</persName>
                    visit Omsk, but said <persName>Webster</persName> party likewise disposed in
                    this as in other matters to accept Bolshevik assurance that it was nothing.
                        <persName corresp="#p_TAR1">Thomson</persName>, Omsk,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d167fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_TAR1">Alfred R. Thomson</persName>, Consul at Irkutsk,
                        detailed to Omsk.</note> April 5, reported thousand prisoners near there
                    fully equipped under German officers and suggested that arming prisoners might
                    be with German approval to oppose Japanese invasion. <persName corresp="#p_JD1"
                        >Jenkins</persName>, Chita, 13th, reports decree of local Soviet government
                    declaring prisoners free as other inhabitants. You see reports disagree.
                        <persName corresp="#p_RLCR1">Robins</persName> already cabled <persName
                        corresp="#p_DHP1">Davison</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TLCWB1"
                        >Thompson</persName>, that <persName>Webster</persName> investigation
                    “admirably done.”</p>
                <pb facs="0216" n="126" xml:id="pg_126"/>
                <p>Petrograd press says Chinese press report two detachments of English and American
                    troops arrived Harbin. Is it true? <persName corresp="#p_CJK1"
                        >Caldwell</persName> wires Chinese cruiser arrived at Vladivostok.</p>
                <p>American Consul, Petrograd, reports Viborg surrounded and rumored that few
                    Russian vessels sunk in Finnish ports to avoid German capture. See <persName
                        corresp="#p_RLCR1">Robins</persName>’s cable <persName corresp="#p_TLCWB1"
                        >Thompson</persName> through <persName corresp="#p_DHP1">Davison</persName>.
                    Passengers [reference my] 108, <persName corresp="#p_DHP1"
                        >Davison</persName>.<note n="1" xml:id="d167fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
